        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1979-04-12T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1979-04-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="134"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d134">
                <head>134. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_BZ_1">Brzezinski</persName>) to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d134fn1">Source: Carter Library, National
                        Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material, President’s Daily <gloss
                            target="#t_CIA_1">CIA</gloss> Brief File, Box 18, 4/1/79–4/6/79. Secret;
                        Sensitive. <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> wrote: “Zbig” and
                        initialed at the top of the memorandum.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1979-04-12">April 12, 1979</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Daily Report</item>
                </list>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to India.]</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Indian Reaction to U.S. Aid Cutoff to Pakistan:</hi> The
                    decision to cut off aid to Pakistan<note n="2" xml:id="d134fn2">See <ref
                            target="#d335">Document 335</ref>.</note> is interpreted in New Delhi as
                    confirmation that Islamabad is developing nuclear weapons. As a result, <gloss
                        target="#t_CIA_1">CIA</gloss> believes the <persName corresp="#p_DM_1"
                        >Desai</persName> government’s stated policy not to develop a nuclear
                    arsenal will probably be subjected to heavy pressure. Although New Delhi has not
                    yet made an official statement, the government is likely to be <pb facs="0413"
                        n="368" xml:id="pg_368"/> pressed in Parliament for an official assessment
                    of the implications for its own nuclear program.<note n="3" xml:id="d134fn3">In
                        the left-hand margin next to this paragraph, <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1"
                            >Carter</persName> wrote: “Tell Cy to try to head this off—We’re losing
                        both ways.”</note> (C)</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to India.]</p>
            </div>
        </body>
